# Read in dataset
Data <- read.csv('all-states-history.csv')

# Convert the 'date' column to a Date object and create 'months_of_covid'
Data$date <- as.Date(Data$date)
Data$year <- as.numeric(format(Data$date, "%Y"))
Data$month <- as.numeric(format(Data$date, "%m"))
Data$months_of_covid <- (Data$year - 2020) * 12 + Data$month - (1 - 1)

Data$month_year <- paste(month.name[(Data$months_of_covid - 1) %% 12 + 1], 2020 + (Data$months_of_covid - 1) %/% 12)


# Calculating daily new positive cases to avoid double counting our values
Data <- Data %>%
  arrange(state, date) %>%
  group_by(state) %>%
  mutate(daily_positive = positive - lag(positive, default = first(positive))) %>%
  ungroup()

# Summarize daily new positive cases by months of covid
monthly_positive_cases <- Data %>%
  group_by(months_of_covid) %>%
  summarize(total_positive = sum(daily_positive, na.rm = TRUE))
# Summarize daily new positive cases by state and months of covid
monthly_positive_cases_by_state <- Data %>%
  group_by(state, months_of_covid, month_year) %>%
  summarize(total_positive = sum(daily_positive, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ungroup()

Basically, using this distribution on a linear regression model starts to run into problems on a timescale. Such as many more cases we can expect with each additional month. Based on the outcomes, this approach will not be ideal.

Because I am more interested in predicting number of cases each month X based on a number of variable, we will be looking at different type of distribution.

This is more like it. Our distribution is skewed right. This is because in the starting months, there were many small values testing positive. This increased later on, as we can see in the tail, and also caused an additional double volume in smaller number of positive tests as the pandemic wore off.

We will now log these values because of the skew and also filter out the first 3 months of the pandemic where only a handful of states had positive results.

final_merged_data <- final_merged_data %>%
  mutate(log_total_positive = log(total_positive + 1))

# Initialize an empty list to store plots
plot_list <- list()
morans_list <-list()

# Loop through each unique month
for(month in unique(final_merged_data$month_year)){
  # Subset data for the specific month
  subset_data <- final_merged_data[final_merged_data$month_year == month, ]

  # Create neighbors and weights for the subset data
  neighbors <- poly2nb(subset_data, queen = FALSE)
  weights <- nb2listw(neighbors, style = "W")

  # Perform Moran's test
  state_moran <- moran.test(subset_data$log_total_positive, weights)

  # Create a base R plot (Moran plot) for each month
  plot_name <- paste("Moran Plot - Month:", subset_data$month_year[1])
  moran_plot <- moran.plot(subset_data$log_total_positive, weights, main = plot_name)

  # Store the plot and values in lists
    plot_list[[as.character(month)]] <- moran_plot
    morans_list[[as.character(month)]] <- list(
    Moran_I = state_moran$estimate["Moran I statistic"],
    Expectation = state_moran$estimate["Expectation"],
    Variance = state_moran$estimate["Variance"],
    p_value = state_moran$p.value)
}

# Convert the list to a dataframe for easier viewing and analysis
morans_i_df <- do.call(rbind, morans_list)
rownames(morans_i_df) <- names(morans_list)

# Print the Moran's I values dataframe
print(morans_i_df)

Spatial Error Modeling

In a spatial error model, we assume that our errors (our residuals) are dependent on lagged error terms. In practice, this generally means that we’re assuming that spatial auto-correlation is due to a variable we have not accounted for.

err <- errorsarlm(formula = log_total_positive ~ months_of_covid + PoliticalPartiesRepublicanLeanRep + PoliticalPartiesDemocratLeanDem + densityMi, 
  data = final_merged_data,
  listw = nweights)
summary(err)

We have a strongly positive, statistically significant \(\lambda\) value, indicating that our errors are positively autocorrelated. We also have statistically significant, still-negative, coefficients for all variables.

Note that, unlike the case of our spatial lag model, we can interpret the coefficients directly. This is because the observed autocorrelation in our OLS residuals is assumed to be due to adjacent residuals, not lagged response variables.

Inspecting a map for autocorrelation in model residuals, we again see a distribution that leads us to suspect that we’ve eliminated spatial autocorrelation.

Running further analysis to decide on our model of choice.

Akaike Information Criterion

The AIC is a statistic used to evaluate model fit.

AIC(ols, err, lag)
##     df      AIC
## ols  6 2147.745
## err  7 1975.573
## lag  7 1989.123

On this basis, we should choose the spatial error model because it has the smallest value. Similarly, we could choose the model based on the log-likelihood alone—this is similar to the AIC, but not penalize the model for overfitting. We can examine the relationships between these evaluative criteria by printing an ANOVA table…

Log-Likelihood

anova(err, lag)
##     Model df    AIC  logLik
## err     1  7 1975.6 -980.79
## lag     2  7 1989.1 -987.56

We are attempting to minimize the AIC and maximize the log-likelihood. In this case, these criteria are both met by the err model.

Lagrange Multiplier Tests

A lagrange multiplier test is another common means for evaluating the appropriateness of spatial model. This diagnostic tests the results of an OLS model for a range of forms of spatial dependence:

  1. Error dependence (called LMerr).
  2. A missing spatially lagged dependent variable (called LMlag).
  3. Error dependence robust to the possible presence of missing lagged dependent variable (called RLMerr, for Robust).
  4. A missing lagged dependent variable robust to the possible presence of error dependence (called RLMlag for Robust).
legrange <- lm.LMtests(ols, nweights, test='all')
legrange

Both of our non-robust tests are statistically significant, so we turn to robust tests. Between our two robust forms, the error model has a higher LM value and lower p-value. This suggests that the error model is the more appropriate model, agreeing with our model evaluation using the AIC and Log-likelihood metrics.

Reflecting on this, I agree that the Error model is best suited. Despite the lockdown, the pandemic spread for many reasons beyond the variables I used.Taking this into account, we finde that the impacts of the pandemic were felt hardest by sparely populated Blue states. This goes against may assumptions we had on the rate of infection. It is likely that denser cities had more healthcare infrastructure or had populations easier to reach with vaccines. It is also likely that the slightly reduced outcomes for republican states was from fewer tests being carried out.

All these parameters require deeper investigation and further analysis using qualitative and other quantitative measures to fully understand what went wrong.
